Interesting work, Dan!

I have a few concerns:

(1) StarlingX has systemd v21*9* with a lot of CentOS/Red Hat patches and a few StarlingX patches (let's call it "v219+"); not systemd v21*7*. Thankfully, the differences between v217 and v219+ in the affected file "src/udev/udev-builtin-net_id.c" are not a lot, but please take a look. If you need help, let me know. I will send the patched version of this file to you in private via internal e-mail. The Debian version can be seen at this link:

https://salsa.debian.org/systemd-team/systemd/-/blob/89c3c7aaadc5b7f79d9f9f151ae9ca3df3e44f6a/src/udev/udev-builtin-net_id.c#L344

The CentOS version can be acquired here:

http://vault.centos.org/7.9.2009/updates/Source/SPackages/systemd-219-78.el7_9.3.src.rpm
https://git.centos.org/rpms/systemd/tree/5bd4b19eea06089a98698b897134af7e9a22b7d4

(2) I am concerned about the following differences between v219+ and v247 in the dev_pci_slot() function:

v219+
  for (dent = readdir(dir); dent != NULL; dent = readdir(dir)) {
          int i;
          char *rest;
          char *address;

          if (dent->d_name[0] == '.')
                  continue;
          i = strtol(dent->d_name, &rest, 10);
          if (rest[0] != '\0')
                  continue;
          if (i < 1)
                  continue;
          snprintf(str, sizeof(str), "%s/%s/address", slots, dent->d_name);
          if (read_one_line_file(str, &address) >= 0) {
                  /* match slot address with device by stripping the function */
                  if (strneq(address, udev_device_get_sysname(names->pcidev), strlen(address)))
                          hotplug_slot = i;
                  free(address);
          }

          if (hotplug_slot > 0)
                  break;
  }


v247
  hotplug_slot_dev = names->pcidev;
  while (hotplug_slot_dev) {
          if (sd_device_get_sysname(hotplug_slot_dev, &sysname) < 0)
                  continue;

          FOREACH_DIRENT_ALL(dent, dir, break) {
                  int i;
                  char str[PATH_MAX];
                  _cleanup_free_ char *address = NULL;

                  if (dot_or_dot_dot(dent->d_name))
                          continue;

                  r = safe_atoi(dent->d_name, &i);
                  if (r < 0 || i <= 0)
                          continue;

                  /* match slot address with device by stripping the function */
                  if (snprintf_ok(str, sizeof str, "%s/%s/address", slots, dent->d_name) &&
                      read_one_line_file(str, &address) >= 0 &&
                      startswith(sysname, address)) {
                          hotplug_slot = i;

                          /* We found the match between PCI device and slot. However, we won't use the
                           * slot index if the device is a PCI bridge, because it can have other child
                           * devices that will try to claim the same index and that would create name
                           * collision. */
                          if (naming_scheme_has(NAMING_BRIDGE_NO_SLOT) && is_pci_bridge(hotplug_slot_dev))
                                  hotplug_slot = 0;

                          break;
                  }
          }
          if (hotplug_slot >= 0)
                  break;
          if (sd_device_get_parent_with_subsystem_devtype(hotplug_slot_dev, "pci", NULL, &hotplug_slot_dev) < 0)
                  break;
          rewinddir(dir);
  }


The logic in the inner "if" block is slightly different in the two versions.

In v219+, the code reads the PCI address from the file .../address and breaks out of the loop if the PCI address *starts with* the PCI device's system name ("sysname"). (That is strneq(...) is the same as strncmp(...) == 0.)

However, in v247 with the naming scheme that this patch introduces, the NAMING_BRIDGE_NO_SLOT feature is enabled. If the is_pci_bridge(hotplug_slot_dev) returns true, then hotplug_slot will be reset from "i" to zero. This still breaks out of the loop, but will result in different behaviour, because the following code sections always check that "hotplug_slot" is > 0. Please see below.

All this to say, I believe that we should not use the NAMING_BRIDGE_NO_SLOT naming scheme feature, and just use a new bitmask value to distinguish StarlingX's naming schemes from other naming schemes.

Thank you,

Vefa



